{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"820eb522-a198-4ecb-9803-ffb0e3dd95ac","content":"Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsException<T>()`, which is more precise and lets you inspect the exception:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName);\n}\n```\n\n**Why this is better:**\n\n- **Pinpoints the throwing line** — `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line in the test throws, masking bugs.\n- **Lets you assert on the exception** (message, `ParamName`, inner exception, etc.)\n- **Async-friendly** variant: `await Assert.ThrowsExceptionAsync<T>(...)`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b55e8f1c-a807-4601-99c2-e8a881693a52","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a straightforward knowledge question — no tools needed.\n\nThe modern approach is to use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>()` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>()` (xUnit/NUnit).","outputTokens":303,"requestId":"1BEF:AAEEE:4AF1CD:557EC6:6A03D633"},"id":"a9e63ea1-a835-44ec-8976-b8af29b89660","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:39:06.547Z","parentId":"3758d5e2-2a33-4943-8147-be4d7a2a4c06"}
